So if we hash it like `hash(safe_mul(x,y);my_repo/name)`, then even if copiers copy this hash to chain and take the code later, validators then append the repo name where its pulled from and check hash of `hash(safe_mul(x,y);their_repo/name)` which is different from what they submitted to chain

It solves the "copy of hash in same block" problem. You would still need to compare the hashes of just the expression as well in the validator code to check if someone did not copy a gene after it was submitted to hf

So
1. Submit hash(gene+repo) to chain.
2. Submit gene to hf (13s later or once transaction has been included in block). 

Validator:
- pull all hashes and pull gene + hf repo
- hash(gene+hf_repo) and check if it matches the on chain hash.
- hash(gene) and compare against the local gene database to see if same gene was already submitted and compare the on-chain block numbers.
